Section 1:
1 L.D. 1540
2 Date: (Filing No. S- )
3 HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 SENATE
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 624, L.D. 1540, “Resolve, to Direct the
10 Department of Health and Human Services, Office of MaineCare Services to Create the
11 Complex Care Assistant Training Program”
12 Amend the resolve by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'Resolve, Directing the Maine Developmental Disabilities Council to Examine the
14 Unmet Needs of Children Who Need Skilled Medical Care'
15 Amend the resolve by striking out all of the emergency preamble.
16 Amend the resolve by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
17 'Sec. 1. Maine Developmental Disabilities Council to convene work group
18 to examine needs of families of children who need skilled medical care.
19 Resolved: That the Maine Developmental Disabilities Council, established by the Maine
20 Revised Statutes, Title 5, section 12004-I, subsection 66, referred to in this resolve as "the
21 council," shall convene a work group, referred to in this resolve as "the work group," to
22 examine the unmet needs of children in the State who need skilled medical care and
23 families of those children. Working in partnership with the children and youth with special
24 health care needs program within the Department of Health and Human Services, Maine
25 Center for Disease Control and Prevention, the work group shall:
26 1. Determine the number of children in the State with special health care needs who
27 require skilled nursing;
28 2. Determine the number of children with special health care needs under department
29 rule Chapter 101: MaineCare Benefits Manual, Chapters II and III, Section 40 and Section
30 96 who are:
31 A. Eligible for skilled medical support;
32 B. Currently receiving services;
33 C. Receiving a different number of hours of services per week compared to the number
34 to which the children are entitled and what the difference is;
Page 1 - 132LR1416(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 624, L.D. 1540
1 D. On waiting lists for services in each county; and
2 E. On more than one waiting list under paragraph D and how many;
3 3. Recommend a method to collect data systematically for any data components in
4 subsection 2 that are not available;
5 4. Identify the variety of unmet needs for children with special health care needs and
6 families of those children and develop recommendations so that those children are able to
7 get their needs met;
8 5. Identify the best method to compensate families with children who need skilled
9 medical care who are unable to find appropriate professionals to provide care resulting in
10 parents providing services themselves;
11 6. Consider benefits and disadvantages to amending Department of Health and Human
12 Services rule Chapter 101: MaineCare Benefits Manual, Chapters II and III, Section 40 or
13 Section 96, developing a federal waiver for children with complex medical needs or a
14 combination of these strategies or other methods; and
15 7. Develop recommendations to ensure that medical assessments are conducted on
16 children who need them through existing or expanded services or funding streams.
17 Sec. 2. Work group membership. Resolved: That the work group convened
18 pursuant to section 1 must include, but is not limited to, members appointed by the council
19 as follows:
20 1. A representative from the children and youth with special health care needs program
21 within the Department of Health and Human Services, Maine Center for Disease Control
22 and Prevention;
23 2. A representative from the Department of Health and Human Services, Maine Center
24 for Disease Control and Prevention, Division of Public Health Nursing;
25 3. A representative from the Department of Health and Human Services, Office of
26 MaineCare Services with expertise in the early and periodic screening, diagnostic treatment
27 program;
28 4. Two parents or guardians of children who require complex medical care;
29 5. A representative of an agency providing home health services;
30 6. A representative of an agency providing private duty nursing services;
31 7. A physician, physician's assistant or nurse practitioner who takes care of pediatric
32 patients with complex medical needs;
33 8. A representative from children's behavioral health services within the Department
34 of Health and Human Services;
35 9. A representative from the State Board of Nursing; and
36 10. A representative from the council.
37 Sec. 3. Convening of work group; staffing assistance; funding. Resolved:
38 That the council shall provide the necessary resources to organize and support the work of
39 the work group convened pursuant to this resolve, including convening and providing any
40 necessary staffing services for the work group.
Page 2 - 132LR1416(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 624, L.D. 1540
1 Sec. 4. Report. Resolved: That the council shall submit a report, no later than
2 January 31, 2026, that includes a summary of the findings of the work group along with
3 recommendations and any suggested legislation to the Joint Standing Committee on Health
4 and Human Services. The committee shall review the findings and recommendations of
5 the report and may report out legislation to implement recommendations related to the
6 report in the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.'
7 Amend the resolve by striking out all of the emergency clause.
8 Amend the resolve by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
9 section number to read consecutively.
10 SUMMARY
1111 This amendment replaces the resolve, changes the title and removes the emergency
1122 preamble and emergency clause. The amendment requires the Maine Developmental
1133 Disabilities Council to convene a work group to examine the unmet needs of children who
1144 require skilled medical care and families of those children. The council must submit a
1155 report to the Joint Standing Committee on Health and Human Services no later than January
1166 31, 2026. The committee is authorized to report out legislation related to the report to the
1177 Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
1188 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
1199 (See attached)
Page 3 - 132LR1416(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
